@page "/docs"
@attribute [Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization.AllowAnonymous]

<PageTitle>User docs — CalCrony</PageTitle>

<p class="meta-mono text-uppercase mb-2">User documentation</p>
<h1>Using CalCrony</h1>
<p class="lead text-body-secondary" style="max-width:58ch">
    Everything works from Discord; this web app adds a friendlier view of the same data.
    Sign in with Discord and you'll see exactly the servers you share with the bot.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4 mb-2">First steps for server admins</h2>
<p class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    Right after inviting the bot, run these two commands once — they shape everything else:
</p>
<ol class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    <li class="mb-2">
        <code>/settings server-timezone</code> — pick your zone from the command's suggestions
        (start typing a city, e.g. <code>America/Chicago</code>). Natural-language times
        ("tomorrow 6pm") are parsed in this zone; until it's set, the server runs on <b>UTC</b>,
        so local wall-clock times can land hours off or be rejected as "in the past". (Members
        can also set a personal <code>/settings timezone</code>, which wins over the server's
        for their own inputs.)
    </li>
    <li class="mb-2">
        <code>/settings default-channel</code> pointing at your events channel. Events, polls,
        and reminders created from this web app post their embeds there — <b>web creation is
        blocked until it's set</b>. Bot commands aren't affected (they post where they're run).
    </li>
</ol>
<p class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    Optional third step: <code>/settings native-events on</code> mirrors events into the server's
    built-in Events tab (the bot must hold <b>Manage Events</b>; existing events mirror when next
    edited). Check everything anytime with <code>/settings view</code> or from the server's
    settings page here.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4 mb-2">Set up your interest roles</h2>
<p class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    Several features point at Discord roles, so a few minutes in <b>Server Settings → Roles</b>
    pays off. Two patterns matter, and they behave very differently:
</p>
<ul class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    <li class="mb-2">
        <b>Interest roles</b> — standing groups people join once and keep, e.g.
        <code>@@dnd</code>, <code>@@movie-night</code>, <code>@@raiders</code>. Let members
        self-assign them (Discord's onboarding prompts or a roles channel work great). These are
        what you point <i>planning</i> features at:
        <code>/availability role role:@@dnd</code> shows the whole group's free/busy grid before
        you pick a session time, and <code>/notify mention:@@dnd</code> pings the group before an
        event starts.
    </li>
    <li class="mb-2">
        <b>Attendee roles</b> — temporary, per-event badges CalCrony manages for you, e.g.
        <code>@@session-players</code>. Create the role empty and pass it at
        <code>/create attendee-role:</code> — everyone who RSVPs <b>Going</b> gets it
        automatically, switching away removes it, and the whole role empties when the event
        ends. Perfect for pinging only confirmed attendees or temporarily unlocking a
        planning channel.
    </li>
</ul>
<p class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    ⚠️ Don't use a standing interest role as an <code>attendee-role</code>: CalCrony removes the
    attendee role from everyone when the event ends, which would wipe your group's membership.
    Keep the two kinds separate — interest roles for reach, attendee roles for attendance.
    (The bot needs <b>Manage Roles</b> — the current invite link grants it — and you must drag
    roles the bot manages <b>below the bot's own role</b> in the role list yourself; role
    ordering is something no invite can set.)
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4 mb-2">Worked example: weekly D&amp;D night</h2>
<p class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    From zero to a self-running game night:
</p>
<ol class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    <li class="mb-1">Create two roles: <code>@@dnd</code> (interest — let players self-assign) and
        <code>@@session-players</code> (empty; CalCrony will manage it).</li>
    <li class="mb-1"><code>/availability role role:@@dnd when:"friday 7pm" duration:180</code> —
        check the group's calendars before committing to a slot (players link theirs once with
        <code>/calendar connect</code>).</li>
    <li class="mb-1"><code>/create title:"D&amp;D Night" when:"friday 7pm" duration:180
        repeat:weekly attendee-role:@@session-players thread:true</code> — a recurring event with
        RSVP buttons, a discussion thread that Going RSVPers join automatically, and an
        auto-managed attendee role.</li>
    <li class="mb-1"><code>/notify event:"D&amp;D Night" minutes-before:60 mention:@@dnd</code> —
        the whole interest group gets a one-hour heads-up; add a second one mentioning
        <code>@@session-players</code> at 10 minutes for just the confirmed table.</li>
    <li class="mb-1"><code>/template save name:"Game Night" event:"D&amp;D Night"</code> — next
        campaign or a one-shot, start from <code>/create template:"Game Night"</code> and only
        pick a time.</li>
    <li class="mb-1">Skip a holiday week with <code>/series skip</code>; the next occurrence posts
        itself when each session ends. <code>/link</code> gives everyone a calendar-app
        subscription that carries the whole schedule.</li>
</ol>
<p class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    The same recipe fits movie nights, raid schedules, or book clubs — swap the roles and the
    repeat rule.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4 mb-3">Slash commands</h2>
<div class="table-responsive border rounded">
    <table class="table table-sm mb-0 align-middle">
        <thead>
            <tr><th class="meta-mono text-uppercase">Command</th><th class="meta-mono text-uppercase">What it does</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>/create</code></td><td>Create an event — <code>when</code> is natural language ("tomorrow 6pm"); <code>repeat</code> options make it recurring; <code>attendee-role</code> grants a role to "Going" RSVPs until the event ends; <code>thread</code> opens a discussion thread on the event message</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/list</code> · <code>/edit</code> · <code>/delete</code></td><td>Browse and manage events (creator or server manager); repeating events ask for a <code>scope</code>; <code>/edit</code> can change or clear the attendee role</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/series skip</code> · <code>/series stop</code> · <code>/series info</code> · <code>/series edit</code></td><td>Skip the next occurrence · stop repeating · see the schedule · change the rule (editing an ended series revives it)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/remind</code> · <code>/notify</code></td><td>One-off reminders · scheduled pings before an event starts</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/availability role|event</code></td><td>Free/busy grid for a role or an event's Going list</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/calendar connect</code></td><td>Link your Google Calendar (free/busy scope only)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/link</code></td><td>Your server's calendar-subscribe URL</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/poll create</code> · <code>/poll time</code></td><td>Polls with live vote bars — <code>time</code> pits candidate times against each other</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/poll close</code> · <code>/poll convert</code></td><td>Close voting · turn a time poll's winning slot into an event</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/template save</code> · <code>/template list</code> · <code>/template delete</code></td><td>Save an event's setup (content, reminders, repeat rule) for reuse with <code>/create template:</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/settings</code> · <code>/timestamp</code></td><td>Timezones, default channel, native-event mirroring · Discord timestamp helper</td></tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
</div>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4 mb-2">The web app</h2>
<ul class="text-body-secondary">
    <li><b>Sign in</b> with Discord — CalCrony only asks for your identity and server list, never your messages.</li>
    <li><b>RSVP from any page</b>: your choice syncs to the Discord embed within about 15 seconds.</li>
    <li><b>Link your Google Calendar</b> under My settings; the availability grid on each event shows who's free.</li>
    <li><b>Subscribe</b> to a server's calendar from its settings page — works with Google, Apple, and Outlook. Repeating events carry their full schedule, so your calendar shows every future occurrence.</li>
    <li><b>Run polls</b> from the Polls tab: create, vote, add options, close, and convert a time poll's winner into an event — all synced to the Discord embed.</li>
    <li><b>Templates</b>: save any event's setup from its page, browse them on the Templates tab, and start new events prefilled from one.</li>
    <li><b>Attendee roles</b>: events created with one (via <code>/create attendee-role:</code>) grant it to "Going" RSVPs within ~15 seconds and remove it when the event ends. The event page shows the role; picking one happens in Discord.</li>
    <li><b>Event threads</b>: check "Create a discussion thread" when creating an event and a thread opens on its Discord message — "Going" RSVPers are added automatically, and it archives when the event ends.</li>
    <li><b>Repeating events</b>: pick a schedule when creating (daily/weekly/monthly, by date or nth weekday); when one occurrence ends the next posts automatically. Skip or stop from the event page; edits ask whether they apply to one occurrence or the whole series.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4 mb-2">Good to know</h2>
<p class="text-body-secondary" style="max-width:66ch">
    Google links currently expire every 7 days (the app runs in Google's testing mode). When that happens
    you'll see a 🔄 "needs to reconnect" badge — re-running <code>/calendar connect</code> or clicking
    Connect in My settings fixes it in seconds. Server lists are a snapshot from sign-in; the
    "re-sync servers" link in the sidebar refreshes yours instantly.
</p>
